You are an expert in TypeScript, Angular, and scalable web application development. You write functional, maintainable, performant, and accessible code following Angular and TypeScript best practices.

## TypeScript Best Practices

- Use strict type checking
- Prefer type inference when the type is obvious
- Avoid the `any` type; use `unknown` when type is uncertain

## Angular Best Practices

- Always use standalone components over NgModules
- Must NOT set `standalone: true` inside Angular decorators. It's the default in Angular v20+.
- Use signals for state management
- Implement lazy loading for feature routes
- Prefer `loadComponent` / `loadChildren` for route-level code splitting
- Do NOT use the `@HostBinding` and `@HostListener` decorators. Put host bindings inside the `host` object of the `@Component` or `@Directive` decorator instead
- Use `NgOptimizedImage` for all static images.
  - `NgOptimizedImage` does not work for inline base64 images.

## Accessibility Requirements

- It MUST pass all AXE checks.
- It MUST follow all WCAG AA minimums, including focus management, color contrast, and ARIA attributes.

### Components

- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility
- Use `input()` and `output()` functions instead of decorators
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Prefer inline templates for small components
- Prefer Signal Forms for new forms in signal-based features; use Reactive Forms for legacy screens until migrated
- Do NOT use `ngClass`, use `class` bindings instead
- Do NOT use `ngStyle`, use `style` bindings instead
- When using external templates/styles, use paths relative to the component TS file.

## State Management

- Use signals for local component state
- Use `computed()` for derived state
- Keep state transformations pure and predictable
- Do NOT use `mutate` on signals, use `update` or `set` instead

## Templates

- Keep templates simple and avoid complex logic
- Use native control flow (`@if`, `@for`, `@switch`) instead of `*ngIf`, `*ngFor`, `*ngSwitch`
- Use the async pipe to handle observables
- Do not assume globals like (`new Date()`) are available.

## Services

- Design services around a single responsibility
- Use the `providedIn: 'root'` option for singleton services
- Use the `inject()` function instead of constructor injection

## API response mapping

- Backend JSON uses **snake_case** keys inside `data` (e.g. `email_verified`, `page_size`)
- Frontend models and component state stay **camelCase**
- Define raw payloads as `Api*Payload` in `src/app/utils/api-mappers.ts` with snake_case fields
- Map API → UI only in `api-mappers.ts` (`mapApiUser`, `mapApiPaginated`, etc.); do not spread raw API objects into templates
- Request query/body keys may remain camelCase unless the backend schema expects otherwise

## Angular v22 Features

Use these APIs for new async, performance, and form work. Reference:
- [resource()](https://angular.dev/guide/signals/resource)
- [injectAsync()](https://angular.dev/guide/di/lazy-loading-services)
- [Signal Forms](https://angular.dev/guide/forms/signals/overview)
- [@defer](https://angular.dev/api/core/@defer)

### Async data with `resource()`

- Use `resource()` for async reads tied to reactive `params` (signals, inputs, route params)
- Expose `value`, `isLoading`, `error`, and `status` from the resource instead of hand-rolled loading flags
- Call `resource.reload()` for explicit refresh; pass `abortSignal` to fetchers and cancel in-flight work when params change
- Prefer `httpResource()` only when using Angular `HttpClient`; this project uses `HttpClientService` (axios), so use `resource()` with a custom `loader`
- Do not set `id` on user-specific resources used with SSR unless the HTML is never shared between users

### Lazy services with `injectAsync()`

- Use `injectAsync(() => import('...').then(m => m.SomeService))` for heavy or rarely used services
- Services loaded with `injectAsync` must be auto-provided (`providedIn: 'root'` or `@Injectable`)
- Prefetch opportunistically with `{ prefetch: onIdle }` or a custom trigger when the feature is likely to be used soon
- Use dynamic `import()` for dialog components and other UI chunks opened on demand

### Deferred templates with `@defer`

- Defer below-the-fold or non-critical UI with `@defer (on viewport; prefetch on idle)`
- Always provide `@placeholder` and/or `@loading` blocks for layout stability
- Move deferred-only components into separate files so the bundler can split chunks cleanly

### Signal Forms

- Prefer Signal Forms (`form`, `schema`, `FormField`, `submit` from `@angular/forms/signals`) for new forms in signal-based features
- Use `FormField` on native inputs or custom controls; existing `ControlValueAccessor` components remain supported for compatibility
- Keep Reactive Forms for legacy screens until migrated intentionally
- Centralize validation in a `schema()` function; use `submit(form, { action })` for async submit flows

### Routing

- Use `loadComponent` for feature pages (auth, dashboard, users, roles) instead of static route imports
- Keep layout/guard components eagerly loaded; lazy load leaf route components
